Consider the following code. What is the correct way to change the temperature to 32 degrees Celsius?\n```python
class Temperature:
    def __init__(self, celsius):
        self._celsius = celsius

    @property
    def fahrenheit(self):
        return self._celsius * 9/5 + 32

temp = Temperature(30)
```

What will be the output?\n```python
class A:
    def run(self):
        return "A"
class B(A):
    def run(self):
        return "B"
class C(A):
    def run(self):
        return "C"
class D(B, C):
    pass

d = D()
print(d.run())
```

What is the output of this code?\n```python
class Parent:
    def __init__(self):
        self.value = 5

class Child(Parent):
    def __init__(self):
        self.value = 10

c = Child()
print(c.value)
```

What is the output of the following code snippet?\n```python
class Chain:
    def __init__(self, value):
        self.value = value

    def __getattr__(self, name):
        return f"No such attribute: {name}"

c = Chain(5)
print(c.value)
print(c.non_existent)
```

What is the output?\n```python
class Wallet:
    def __init__(self, amount):
        self.amount = amount

    def __bool__(self):
        return self.amount > 0

w1 = Wallet(50)
w2 = Wallet(0)

if w1:
    print("w1 is True")
if not w2:
    print("w2 is False")
```

What will happen when this code is executed?\n```python
class Math:
    @staticmethod
    def add(x, y):
        return self.x + self.y

print(Math.add(2, 3))
```

What is the output of this code snippet?\n```python
class MyClass:
    @staticmethod
    def add(a, b):
        return a + b

print(MyClass.add(5, 3))
```

Consider the following multilevel inheritance. What will be the output?\n```python
class Grandparent:
    def speak(self):
        print("Grandparent speaking")

class Parent(Grandparent):
    def speak(self):
        print("Parent speaking")

class Child(Parent):
    pass

c = Child()
c.speak()
```

What will be the output of this code?\n```python
class MyClass:
    def __init__(self):
        self.__private_var = 42

obj = MyClass()
try:
    print(obj.__private_var)
except AttributeError:
    print("Error")
```

What will be the output of the following code?\n```python
class Vector:
    def __init__(self, x, y):
        self.x = x
        self.y = y

    def __add__(self, other):
        return Vector(self.x + other.x, self.y + other.y)

    def __repr__(self):
        return f"Vector({self.x}, {self.y})"

v1 = Vector(2, 4)
v2 = Vector(3, 5)
print(v1 + v2)
```

What will be the output for the following code?\n```python
class test:
    def __init__(self, a):
        self.a = a
    def display(self):
        print(self.a)

obj = test()
obj.display()
```

What will be the output of the following code?\n```python
class A:
    def __init__(self, x=1):
        self.x = x

class der(A):
    def __init__(self, y=2):
        super().__init__()
        self.y = y

obj = der()
print(obj.x, obj.y)
```

